Name: UVB-76 The Buzzer Ch1
Comment: Russian-based military station that frequently broadcasts Monolit format messages in Russian.

Name: UVB-76 The Buzzer Ch2
Comment: It is believed that the buzzer is not directly modulated but actually recorded by a active microphone, as there have been reports of hearing background chatter while the buzzer was on.

Name: CIS MFSK-16 XPA Ch1
Comment: CIS MFSK-16, is a 14-tone MFSK signal said to have origin from Russian Intelligence and Foreign Ministry stations.

Name: CIS MFSK-16 XPB Ch1
Comment: Enigma designation XPB is a custom 16-tone MFSK mode which is believed to be used by Russian intelligence.

Name: CIS MFSK-16 XPB Ch2
Comment: The signal occupies about 2.8 kHz of bandwidth, but the first tone is about 500 Hz away from the designated transmission frequency, making the total bandwidth about 3.3 kHz.

Name: CIS MFSK-20 XPA Ch1
Comment: CIS MFSK-20, is a 17-tone MFSK signal said to have origin from Russian Intelligence and Foreign Ministry stations.

Name: Mazielka Ch1
Comment: Mazielka (X06) is a diplomatic selcall system used by the Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs.

Name: Mazielka Ch2
Comment: Used to alert that a Serdolik transmission is going to occur soon, usually on a different frequency.

Name: North Korean Diplo FSK Ch1
Comment: North Korean Diplomatic FSK link, teletype radio diplomatic usage.

Name: Polish Intel Ch1
Comment: One-way broadcast system, used by one of Polish intelligence agencies for delivery of messages to their operatives abroad on fixed schedules.

Name: Polish Intel Ch2
Comment: This mode has very close ties to the analogue broadcasts from the same agency, known by their ENIGMA codes E11, S11a, and M03.

Name: Russian Intel Ch1
Comment: One-way error-correcting broadcast system, used by one of Russian intelligence agencies for delivery of messages to their operatives abroad on fixed schedules.

Name: Russian Intel Ch2
Comment: This system conveys encrypted, nameless binary files, with clear binary headers, stating the ID of the recipient, the date the message was written, its serial number, and its length. Its broadcasts often don't contain messages, and may also carry two messa

Name: The Pip (Day)
Comment: The Pip is the nickname given by radio listeners to a shortwave radio station that broadcasts on the frequency 5448 kHz by day, and 3756 kHz during the night.

Name: The Pip (Night)
Comment: The beep signal is occasionally interrupted by voice messages in Russian. The Pip has been active since around 1986 when its distinctive beeping sound was first recorded by listeners.
